<div class="fourteen_section_2" >
	<div class="lectureQuestion">
		<%= render 'lecture_questions/show', :question => parse_lecture_question(@lecture, 6) %>	
	</div>
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				Spielberg approaches this scene with an agenda. By using these bookends for the story that he’s telling, he creates a very specific context for the rest of the events of the film. We’re forced to see the entire contents of this man’s life in the context of this one moment of extreme emotion and patriotism. Spielberg is forcing you to feel what he wants you to feel––a very specific emotional response. Another phrase for this is “emotional blackmail.” Spielberg gives us no choice regarding how we might want to feel about this moment. There’s no room for us to have our own thoughts or feelings about the events of the film. 
			</p>
			<p>
				If a filmmaker has to tell a story involving some weighty emotional content, what might it look like to present that material in a non-manipulative way?
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="videoContainer">
		<div class="column firstColumn">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				There’s quite a bit of emotion in <em>Tokyo Story</em>. Most of the time, it’s burbling under the surface and not overtly visible, but there are a few moments where it comes to the surface. In one of those scenes, about two-thirds of the way through the film, the mother in the story is staying overnight with her daughter-in-law. 
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="column secondColumn">
			<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/80302245?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff" width="700" height="528" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="lectureQuestion">
		<%= render 'lecture_questions/show', :question => parse_lecture_question(@lecture, 7) %>	
	</div>
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				The mother is feeling a wide range of emotions that have built up over the film. Her own children treat her like a nuisance while her daughter-in-law treats her with much more concern and intimacy. She’s exhorting her daughter-in-law to remarry, telling her that as she gets older, she’ll get lonely. While the mother is speaking about the daughter-in-law, she’s also really talking about herself, revealing her own feelings of loneliness. At this point, the emotions that have been building up throughout the film thus far bubble over to the surface and the mother begins to cry. It’s interesting to compare the way Ozu treats this external expression of emotion in comparison to Spielberg. We see the woman in a medium closeup as she begins to cry. Ozu holds the shot for a few seconds, but then cuts away to the daughter-in-law. As if providing a cue for the audience, the daughter-in-law herself turns to look away from the mother’s expression of emotion. Ozu then cuts to a wide shot with the mother in the foreground but hidden mostly in darkness while she cries. He then goes one step further and has the daughter-in-law get up and turn out the light, as if to give the mother more privacy while she cries.  
			</p>
			<p>
				Ozu doesn’t, however, cut away from the scene. He wants to depict the depth of the mother’s emotions, but he seems to consider it impolite to wallow in her misery. Instead he cuts back to the daughter lying in bed as we hear the sound of the mother continuing to cry, and we see the daughter struggling with her own emotions. 
			</p>
			<p>
				There’s intense emotion happening in this scene, but Ozu seeks simply to depict the depth of the emotion without trying to exploit it and force the viewer to feel it, too. He makes no demands from the viewer, giving her the space to feel about the scene however she chooses. As Donald Richie talked about in your reading from a few weeks ago, Ozu does not ask for our emotional engagement, and so, paradoxically, we more freely give it. 
			</p>
			<p>
				In my mind, Ozu’s approach is “better” because it demonstrates a certain amount of respect for the viewer, treating the viewer as someone capable of making his/her own decisions, not as a child who has to be led by the nose and told exactly what to think and feel. 
			</p>
			<p>
				This objection to the “artificial” inflation of a scene’s emotion goes a long way toward explaining the attempts by some filmmakers to find less manipulative ways to present a story. Both Yasujiro Ozu and Michael Haneke, in the last two films we’ve watched, take pains to avoid the sort of emotional manipulation that is common in much of today’s cinema. Creating deep emotional engagement is certainly one of cinema’s great strengths. Some filmmakers, at least, seem to feel that “with great power comes great responsibility.”
			</p>
			<h3>ENSEMBLE FILM REDUX</h3>
			<p>
				This week we’re revisiting the ensemble film that we first looked at two weeks ago. We’ll see a film that’s a bit more representative of the genre. <em>Me and You and Everyone We Know</em> is also a representation of another classic pattern of narrative cinema, the love story.
			</p>
			<p>
				A quick recap of some of the characteristics of the ensemble film that we laid out last time that you should be on the lookout for: 
			</p>
			<p>
				1) Less complex characterization. Think about how you would describe each character in the film. Does your description consist primarily of one particular trait for most of the characters? Are any of the characters complex?
			</p>
			<p>
				2) Different narrative arc. What constitutes the first act for this film? How long is it? What is the film’s climax, and when does it occur?
			</p>
			<p>
				3) Dangling cause is used prominently. How often do we leave a thread of the story in the midst of an act without seeing it’s consequences until later? 
			</p>
